summarize the following into a single paragraph using positive and lay language.




Background, Motivation, and Vision




Our environments are geęing smarter. We have seen an increasing number of smarts around us such as wearables, voice assistants, service robots, autonomous vehicles, and a broader array of connective objects in IoT. My research creates enabling sensing and actuation technologies on these smart devices to make ambient intelligence more powerful in facilitating the future of work, healthcare, and education, making our physician environments sustainable and accessible to all.




Pillar 1: Create sustainable ambient intelligence




My research creates sustainable computing technologies that lower the carbon footprint of ambient intelligence while improving its practicality in real-world applications. My lab has been developing novel self-sustaining sensing and actuation systems that monitor events and facilitate user activities running on energy harvested from user interactions (e.g., kinetic movement of people). Overall, this research pillar directly addresses sustainability in the design of computing and enables ambient intelligence to be applied with a minimal negative impact on the environment.




Pillar 2: Use ambient intelligence to improve real-world access for people with disabilities




Ambient intelligence also opens new opportunities for making the physical world equally accessible to all.




Speciﬁcally, my research develops systems that can digitize the physical world for accessibility applications, including XR and AI techniques that allow people with disabilities to beęer navigate through a world full of barriers and inaccessible information. My research also creates intelligent sensing and actuation systems that can be easily utilized by people with motor impairments (e.g., users of wheelchairs) for independent living and improved life qualities.




Pillar 3: Create tools to facilitate the development of ambient intelligence




Finally, my research aims to empower everyone to create ambient intelligence. We believe that people should be able to create ambient intelligence as easily as switching a lightbulb. Besides sponsoring the community with toolkits of existing research, my research also seeks general-purpose frameworks and tools that can be easily used by people with various levels of experience for developing ambient intelligent systems. Ongoing research in this pillar includes 1) creating open-source construction kits, and 2) developing programming tools for developers of energy-harvesting self-sustaining IoT systems.

give a one sentence summary based on the following:

Automating operations of objects has made life easier and more convenient for billions of people, especially those with limited motor capabilities. On the other hand, even able-bodied users might not always be able to perform manual operations (e.g., both hands are occupied), and manual operations might be undesirable for hygiene purposes (e.g., contactless devices). As a result, automation systems like motion-triggered doors, remote-control window shades, contactless toilet lids have become increasingly popular in private and public environments. Yet, these systems are hampered by complex building wiring or short battery lifetimes, negating their positive benefits for accessibility, energy saving, healthcare, and other domains. In this paper we explore how these types of objects can be powered in perpetuity by the energy generated from a unique energy source – user interactions, specifically, the manual manipulations of objects by users who can afford them when they can afford them. Our assumption is that users’ capabilities for object operations are heterogeneous, there are desires for both manual and automatic operations in most environments, and that automatic operations are often not needed as frequently for example, an automatic door in a public space is often manually opened many times before a need for automatic operation shows up. The energy harvested by those manual operations would be sufficient to power that one automatic operation. We instantiate this idea by upcycling common everyday objects with devices which have various mechanical designs powered by a general-purpose backbone embedded system. We call these devices, MiniKers. We built a custom driver circuit that can enable motor mechanisms to toggle between generating powers (i.e., manual operation) and actuating objects (i.e., automatic operation). We designed a wide variety of mechanical mechanisms to retrofit existing objects and evaluated our system with a 48-hour deployment study, which proves the efficacy of MiniKers as well as shedding light into this people-as-power approach as a feasible solution to address energy needed for smart environment automation.

Research

As our world becomes increasingly smart with devices like wearables, voice assistants, and autonomous vehicles, Yang’s research focuses on developing technologies that make these devices more sustainable, accessible, and user-friendly. 

First, his research designs eco-friendly sensing systems that power themselves through everyday movements, reducing their environmental impact. For example, MiniKers is a system that harnesses energy from users' manual interactions with objects—such as doors and window shades—to enable sustainable, automatic operations in smart environments, offering an energy-efficient solution to enhance accessibility and convenience while reducing reliance on complex wiring and frequent battery replacements. 

Second, Yang’s work uses ambient intelligence to create tools that make physical spaces more accessible for people with disabilities, helping them navigate and interact with the world independently. For example, WheelPose is a configurable data synthesis pipeline that generates realistic, diverse synthetic data of wheelchair users using motion capture and Unity simulations, validated through human and AI evaluations to improve pose estimation accuracy for wheelchair users.

Last but not least, some of Yang’s effort is on creating easy-to-use toolkits and frameworks to empower anyone, regardless of experience, to build and use ambient intelligence technology, making this advanced field as approachable as turning on a light switch.

Publications

Yang has published 20 conference/journal papers since he joined UCLA, over half of which were led by his group. Yang’s group has been publishing in top venues in Human-Computer Interaction, such as CHI, UIST, and IMWUT. Publishing in these top HCI venues has become significantly more competitive over the recent years. At CHI, for instance, the acceptance rate has hovered around 24-26% in recent years, with over 3,500 submissions in 2023 alone, marking a sharp rise in volume and selectivity. Notably, Yang’s group has also been winning four paper or demo awards, indicating that some of their work ranks the very top in the HCI community. Yang’s other publications also demonstrate his collaboration with other research groups, which further adds to the productivity of his publishing records.

Funding

Yang has had two collaborative NSF SMALL grants soon after he joined UCLA, which demonstrates his ability to quickly learn, carry out, and, most importantly, succeed in fundraising responsibilities. Such early success and experience should well position him to pursue further funding opportunities as he approaches tenure. In the meantime, Yang also raised several industrial gifts, which allowed him to build up a research group early on.
